    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-02T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-02T13:00:00-05:00" n="488"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d488">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115Ev2/17</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-02T19:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 2, 1915, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 3, 4.00 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1728. Naval Attaché <persName corresp="#p_GWR1">Gherardi</persName> returned from
                    Bremen where I sent him to get statements of captains of ships <hi rend="italic"
                        >Evelyn</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Carib</hi>. Both boats sunk by mines, no
                    false directions given by British as reported here, boats simply ran on mine
                    field. Reported to me privately that Scandinavian countries will convoy their
                    merchant vessels using converted merchant vessels with naval crews.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
